Angular has steadily been reducing boilerplate with Signals, and one of the most useful improvements is the model() API.
Before signal-based inputs, creating a custom component that supported two-way binding required defining:

• An @Input() property

• A matching @Output() event ending with Change

• Manual event emission whenever the value changed
With model(), all of that can be replaced with a single reactive signal while keeping the same parent syntax using [(...)].
Let’s see how it works.
The Traditional Approach
Previously, a reusable component exposing two-way binding looked something like this:
import { Component, EventEmitter, Input, Output } from '@angular/core';@Component({
selector: 'app-switch-control',
template: `
<button (click)="toggleValue()">
{{ enabled ? 'Enabled' : 'Disabled' }}
</button>
`
})
export class SwitchControlComponent {
@Input()
enabled = false;
@Output()
enabledChange = new EventEmitter<boolean>();
toggleValue() {
this.enabled = !this.enabled;
this.enabledChange.emit(this.enabled);
}…
